summary: Thank you for reminding about the "Identity Crisis" arc. It definitely is worth revisiting. There are so many good stuff in it!
question: Thank you for reminding about the "Identity Crisis" arc. It definitely is worth revisiting. There are so many good stuff in it!
answer:
There is!!! I mean, there’s also some moments when the different mags get out of tune with each other, particularly about Peter and Mary Jane’s attitude towards Peter’s new identities (in one, they’re both hyped about it and about working together on the designs; in another, Peter is hyped while Mary Jane still worries; in another, Peter actually refuses to leave the Spider-Man identity until he’s encouraged to use the Dusk one by Arthur Stacy and Mary Jane is angry about his attitude; in another), but it still has Norman Osborn bragging about how he’s destroying Peter’s life while he’s redescovering everything he liked about it in the first place, so it’s good. I really hate Norman and villains like him, the “untouchables”. 

Also, here is a reading list, because the issues marked as part of the Identity Crisis don’t include what that page calls the Prelude to it, so you’d miss, for example, how Peter gets the Dusk id or the Bombastic Bag-Man!

summary: I would love to see a ‘verse where Peter and Miles both are active as Spider-man, and both go by that.
body:
I would love to see a ‘verse where Peter and Miles both are active as Spider-man, and both go by that.

Who are you?

I’m Spider-man.

But, you wear black and red and are shorter. Who is the other guy, then?

He’s Spider-man.

But you said you were Spider-man.

I am. So is he. The new girl in the upper east side is also Spider-man.

But how…

Because we’re Spider-man.
